The side length of the smaller square is given by \(\frac{2 - \sqrt{2}}{2}\), which is in the form \(\frac{a - \sqrt{b}}{c}\) with \(a = 2\), \(b = 2\), and \(c = 2\). Here, \(b = 2\) is square-free as it is not divisible by the square of any prime. Thus, \(a + b + c = 2 + 2 + 2 = 6\).

This result is obtained by considering the configuration where the vertex of the square on \(\overline{AE}\) is the vertex opposite to \(B\) in the square (i.e., the top-left vertex when \(B\) is the bottom-right vertex). The slope \(e\) of \(\overline{AE}\) is found to be \(\sqrt{2} - 1\) by solving the system of equations derived from the right triangle condition at \(E\) and the condition that the specified vertex lies on \(\overline{AE}\) and also on \(\overline{EF}\), though the problem only requires it to be on \(\overline{AE}\). The side length \(s\) is then calculated as \(s = \frac{e}{1+e} = \frac{\sqrt{2} - 1}{\sqrt{2}} = \frac{2 - \sqrt{2}}{2}\).

